<br>
     Thats the biggest problem you run into?  Hmmm riggghhht.  I think not, in fact I would'nt even rate it in the top 10 biggest problems.  The biggest problem in a dkp system is without a doubt pricing items fairly.  As far as &quot;throwing casual players a bone&quot;, if you did you would be undermining the entire concept of the system.  The system was born in order to create an impartial and unbiased representation of each players contribution to the system.  You can't just bend the rules and throw somoene a bone.  A player who understands the system will know and accept the way things are going to be when they cut their playing time down.  No one should need to throw them a bone.  In a guild like HnE there are other attractions to being in the guild apart from loot, like content that would not otherwise be seen by the player at all.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ultimately, the hardest part is keeping everyone happy. If your hardcore players feel like they're spinning their wheels , then they're apt to start questioning why thy're carrying the casual players along instead of just joining a hardcore raiding guild.&quot;<br>
<br>
     Again I would have to disagree.  If that's the hardest part of running a guilds dkp system then your doing something incorrectly.  If the system is fair and unbiased people should be (and have been) happy with it without any work (directly towards contentment with the dkp system) from the officers at all.<br>
