<br>
Actually, he misinterpreted both.<br>
<br>
My point wasn't about running a DKP system at all, it was about DKP not being a suitable loot system for a guild made up of both casual and hardcore players.<br>
<br>
DKP works for guilds like HnE because the majority of the guild is hardcore raiders and they are rewarded for their participation.  The few casual players in such a system are content with the (quite good) scraps they pick up and if they're undergeared, they don't really impact the overall performance of the guild.<br>
<br>
In a hybrid (casual/hardcore) guild, a significant percentage of the member base are casual players and therefore would be slow to accumulate DKP.  Heavy raiders would be in a position to buy the best items while a larger group of casual raiders either buy up lesser items or hold out for long periods of time hoping to buy one valuable item.  The net effect of that, is your well geared hardcore players and sub-par geared casual players.  Those sub-par geared players have much more negative an effect on the overall power of the guild than 1-2 casual players would have on a guild like HnE.<br>
<br>
Once again, this really only applies to a guild which is trying to advance in new content, a casual guild which is content to raid older content can obviously be successful with smaller numbers.  A guild like that though to lean more towards the casual side and not attract as many heavy raiders. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=5948">Duke Krazaak Crushbone</a> <<a href="http://www.hneguild.com">Heaven and Earth</a>><BR>
