<br>
So when I buy the first 50 AC BP for 20 DKP one day and then the next day someone buys it for 10DKP you dont think I am gonna think I overpaid?  The net effect would probably be the lowering of all prices accrost the board since no one in their right mind would bid for an item the first 5 times it dropped for fear of overpayment.  I researched bidding systems also and I think they suck ass.  They are subject to outside influence.  Like player A knows that player B wants an item so they intentionally run up the bid price.  Even if the player did not do it intentionally the other player may feel like they did.  Just like an officer loot distribution system where everything may be fair and the player still feels cheated.  Everyone should pay the same.  An item is not worth double dkp just because you got it 4 days before someone else and while the player may initially pay the ransom I promise you when the newness wears off and they just realize they paid 2 weeks more dkp than the next person they are gonna come back and be pissed.<br>
<br>
~Kioti <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=joecool12321>joecool12321</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(7/18/03 11:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntaverncommonsroom.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5270.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> &quot;Like player A knows that player B wants an item so they intentionally run up the bid price.&quot;<br>
<br>
First, if your guild has these problems, you have deeper issues than a loot system, I think. Second, though - it's a silent auction so there's no &quot;running up&quot; the price. <br>
<br>
&quot;An item is not worth double dkp just because you got it 4 days before someone else.&quot;<br>
<br>
Why not? It may not be worth it to *you*, so you can wait four days later (although if it's a nice item, the price won't drop for a while). Supply and demand determine price, not some dictatorial decision passed down from on high. <br>
<br>
--Cabiz <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=chaocle>Chaocle</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://bellsouthpwp.net/c/h/chaord/chaosig.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:green;'>Tavern Patron</span></span><br>  Posts: 175<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(7/18/03 1:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntaverncommonsroom.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5270.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> balance in guild</span><hr size=1> A house divided cannot stand.<br>
I don't think it is possible to have a strong raiding guild and at the same time a strongly casual 'friendly' guild.  The goals and all the things towards meeting those goals do not mesh.  Besides the disparity that will grow between the groups in equipment/experience/ability will cause the raid group to be incompatable with the other.  You can drag along a level 56 to Time.  Even 2 level 65s can be very different because of AAs and items.  Eventually you have to choose a path.  <br>
If you stay too casual, then members will come in and leave as they get bored, or wish to move to other parts of the game.  Then those raider folks will eventually get tired of getting strangers epics while they haven't seen a decent upgrade in several months.<br>
If you go too hardcore raiding, you have to cycle in new uber wannabes because of the burnout or boredom.<br>
If you try to go right down the middle, you can float along a while, but then you have a numbers problem.  If you raid say 3 days a week, your casuals will argue over which 3 days and what time, because they only have 10 hours a week to play.<br>
You can have a casual group inside a raid guild that uses DKP, but they will probably either leave soon out of frustration, or ramp up their play time to catch up.  <br>
A raid guild must also focus its efforts on doing only what will best advance the guild.  Little time for quests.  No time for ego baby sitting.  <br>
Best to pick a goal, then find a guild that shares it.  If your goals change, change guilds. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lochdivine>Loch Divine</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:green;'>Tavern Patron</span></span><br>  Posts: 130<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(7/18/03 5:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntaverncommonsroom.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5270.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ...</span><hr size=1> If you think you can comprise a guild of 100+ people (total in order to have a sure 70 or whatever is needed now on everyday) and everyone will like each other and no one will be childish and try to fuck someone else is just naive.  It happens even in the best guilds anywhere.  And when it does bidding systems fail.  Which they have multiple times.<br>
